erefore it would be unfair to judge the two posts solely based on their numerical ratings. In other words, the quality of a post should be judged relative to other posts on the same topic, rather than to all other posts in general.\n\nSo the subject matter is not inherently more valuable, but it does affect how we should evaluate the quality of a post, and we need a way to control for that in our metrics.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: So for each of his past posts, he was given a rating by three reivewers, which was then averaged. Then all of those ratings for every post were averaged together to get 6.5, right?\nAnswer: Sure, here\'s an example:\n\nLet\'s say that we have a post about a medical study written by an author named John. John\'s post was reviewed by three reviewers, A, B, and C, who gave the post ratings of 8, 9, and 7 respectively. We also know that the average rating for medical study posts written by all authors is 6, and the standard deviation is 2.\n\nTo calculate John\'s AQMi for this post, we can use a Bayesian approach. We can model the distribution of John\'s true ability to write quality posts about medical studies as a normal distribution with a mean of 6.5 (the prior mean) and a standard deviation of 1 (the prior standard deviation). We can then update this distribution based on the ratings given to John\'s post by the three reviewers.\n\nUsing Bayesian updating, we can calculate the posterior distribution of John\'s ability to write quality posts about medical studies based on the ratings he received for this post. The posterior mean would be:\n\nPosterior Mean = ((8-6)*(1/2^2) + (9-6)*(1/2^2) + (7-6)*(1/2^2) + 6.5*(1/1^2)) / ((1/2^2)\\*3 + (1/1^2))\n\nSimplifying this equation gives us:\n\nPosterior Mean = 7.8\n\nSo John\'s AQMi for this post would be 7.8, which reflects his estimated ability to write quality posts about medical studies based on the ratings he received for this particular post and the prior knowledge we have about his abilities.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: So you are assuming his past posts had ratings that were sampled from from a normal distribution with mean of 6.5 and SD of 1?\nAnswer: That\'s correct! The average of all ratings given to John\'s past posts by the three reviewers is first calculated and then that value is averaged across all his posts to obtain the author quality metric for John\'s medical study posts.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: how do you know in this cause it would be a roughly normal distribution? Are you talking about the law of large numbers?\nAnswer: Yes, that\'s correct. The assumption is that the ratings for the past posts follow a normal distribution with a mean of 6.5 and a standard deviation of 1.\n<|im_end|>\n<|im_start|>assistant\n', params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None, extra_args=None), prompt_token_ids: None, prompt_embeds shape: None, lora_request: None, prompt_adapter_request: None.
