rotocol (RTP) packetization, transport, and reception.\n\nThe SCTE-104 ad markers are typically placed in the UDP ancillary data payload of the AES67 stream, and the app would need to be able to read and interpret them to stitch ads to the stream.\n\n\n--- Conversation 2 ---\nQuestion: what is AES67-6\nAnswer: There is no AES67-6 standard in the AES67 family of standards. AES67 is made up of the following standards:\n\n* AES67-2013: AES standard for audio applications of networks - High-performance streaming audio-over-IP interoperability (first edition)\n* AES67-2015: AES standard for audio applications of networks - High-performance streaming audio-over-IP interoperability (second edition)\n* AES67-2018: AES standard for audio applications of networks - High-performance streaming audio-over-IP interoperability (third edition)\n\nThere are also several related standards, such as AES70, which provides a framework for control and monitoring of networked audio devices, and AES67-2015 Amendment 1, which adds support for the SMPTE ST 2110-30 standard for uncompressed audio-over-IP.\n\n\n--- Conversation 3 ---\nQuestion: But you said \nAES67-6 - This is the Technical Recommendation for the use of RTP in AES67 networks, which provides guidelines for Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) packetization, transport, and reception.\nWhat is AES67-6? a section of the AES67 document or a document in itself? Where can I find the AES67-6 to read it\nAnswer: I apologize for the confusion. AES67-6 is not a separate document, but rather a section in the AES67 standard document. Specifically, it is Section 7: Transport of Audio over IP Networks Using RTP (AES67-6-2018). You can find the full AES67 standard document, including Section 7, on the AES website at <https://www.aes.org/publications/standards/search.cfm?docID=100>.\n\n\n--- Conversation 4 ---\nQuestion: Can I access this document freely?\nAnswer: No, the AES67-6 technical recommendation is a paid document and can only be accessed by purchasing it through the AES Standards website or through a subscription to the AES E-Library.\n\n\n--- Conversation 5 ---\nQuestion: Is the SCTE-104 a protocol or standard? What is a difference?\nAnswer: SCTE-104 is a standard, specifically, it is a standard developed by the Society of Cable Telecommunications Engineers (SCTE) that specifies the interface between automation systems and video servers for inserting digital messages into MPEG and SCTE-35 messages.\n\nA protocol, on the other hand, is a set of rules that defines how data is transmitted over a network or communication channel. Protocols can be a part of a standard or can be developed independently. In general, a protocol is a more specific set of rules that governs a particular aspect of communication, while a standard is a broader set of guidelines or specifications that cover multiple aspects of a system or technology.\n<|im_end|>\n<|im_start|>assistant\n", params: SamplingParams(n=1, presence_penalty=0.0, frequency_penalty=0.0, repetition_penalty=1.0, temperature=0.0, top_p=1.0, top_k=0, min_p=0.0, seed=None, stop=[], stop_token_ids=[], bad_words=[], include_stop_str_in_output=False, ignore_eos=False, max_tokens=100, min_tokens=0, logprobs=None, prompt_logprobs=None, skip_special_tokens=True, spaces_between_special_tokens=True, truncate_prompt_tokens=None, guided_decoding=None, extra_args=None), prompt_token_ids: None, prompt_embeds shape: None, lora_request: None, prompt_adapter_request: None.
